Comments I posted several days ago are no longer here, so I'm re-posting:

@anoXmous - That's not a "better" rip, it's not even comparable since that's 720p resolution and this is 1080p. The only reason you came over here and posted that comment is because you're butthurt because I pointed out that there was pixelation in your Extended Dances with Wolves torrent because your bitrates on some of your 1080ps are too low. The difference though, is that what I said was actually the truth, while you are being dishonest just because your ego was apparently bruised. It's very unbecoming. Don't come over to someone elses' torrents and be dishonest just because they made a completely valid criticism of your work.

And @moeburn1, keep in mind that my bitrates and file sizes are optimized for those who store and watch movies on their computers. The bitrates are high enough to look perfect on "normal" sized monitors and low enough to keep download times short and the file size small enough for those who keep large collections of movies on their hard drives. If you plan on watching something on a large HD screen, you're going to need one of the larger file size, higher bitrate torrents. The larger the screen you'll be watching on, the higher the bitrate has to be to maintain picture quality. If you have a large screen, you'll need to experiment too see what bitrate it takes to maintain a quality picture for you particular size screen. So yes, for computer viewing, 2000 is more than enough for a 1080p (YIFY, who is well known for extremely high quality encoding, has bitrates of around 1800-1900 on his 1080p's and they are flawless.) And yes, I always do 2-pass, uneven multi-hexagon motion estimation method, as well as several other "tweaked" settings that I will keep to myself. On a computer sized-monitor, I would put my work very close to, if not just as good as YIFY's.
